o smell foul; to stink (especially of decay)","tags":["intransitive"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to be offensive to the nose, to smell foul; to stink (especially of decay); to be offensive to the senses, faith, or morals; to be vile, repulsive, or disgusting","tags":["broadly","intransitive"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to cause to stink, to fester, to putrefy, to decay","tags":["transitive"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of نَتَنَ (natana) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of نَتِنَ (natina) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"malodorant, stinky, fetid; putrid"}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"Allegedly cognate to Hebrew נָתַן (nātán, “to give”), Aramaic נָתַן (nātan, “to give”), Aramaic נְתַן (nətan, “to give; to put”), Phoenician 𐤉𐤕𐤍 (ytn, “to give”), Ugaritic 𐎊𐎚𐎐 (ytn, “to give”), Ge'ez ነተን (nätän, “to give”), Akkadian 𒋧 (nadānum, “to give”) by specialization to the meaning “give off smell”. Note the Akkadian spelling comes from Sumerian 𒋧 (šum, “to give”), however it is spelt identically to the Semitic Akkadian 𒋧 (šum, “garlic, onion; potent smelling bulb”) possibly indicating an early semantic connection; compare ثُوم (ṯūm).\nMore remote connections are with وَتِين (watīn) and أَدَّى (ʔaddā)."},"ipa":null}